                <note>Horace Traubel was an American poet, essayist, and author. Traubel was also a
                    dedicated Socialist, and one of the founders of the socialist weekly newspaper
                    <hi rend="italic">The Worker</hi>. He is best known for being Whitman's literary
                    executor and author of a nine-volume biography of hitman's final four years
                    (1888-1892), entitled <hi rend="italic">Walt Whitman in Camden</hi>.</note>
            </person>
        </listPerson>

        <listPerson type="family">
            <person xml:id="hmc">
                <persName>Helen Maria Chesnutt</persName>
                <birth when="1880">1880</birth>
                <death when="1969">1969</death>
                <occupation>teacher</occupation>
                <note>Helen Maria Chesnutt was the daughter of Charles Chesnutt. After
                    attending Smith College, she taught Latin at Central High School in Cleveland,
                    Ohio for many years, including to Langston Hughes. She co-authored a Latin
                    textbook, <hi rend="italic">The Road to Latin</hi> (1932) and served on the
                    executive committee of the American Philological Association in 1920. She also
                    authored an influential biography of her father, entitled <hi rend="italic"
                    >Charles Waddell Chesnutt, Pioneer of the Color Line</hi>.</note>
            </person>
        </listPerson>

        <listPerson type="historical">
